00:00:00.120 --> 00:00:03.410
- The following is a
conversation with Eric Weinstein.

00:00:03.410 --> 00:00:05.340
He's a mathematician, economist,

00:00:05.340 --> 00:00:08.760
physicist and the managing
director of Thiel Capital.

00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:10.960
He coined the term and you could say,

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:14.410
is the founder of the
Intellectual Dark Web,

00:00:14.410 --> 00:00:17.370
which is a loosely assembled
group of public intellectuals

00:00:17.370 --> 00:00:20.980
that includes Sam Harris,
Jordan Peterson, Steven Pinker,

00:00:20.980 --> 00:00:24.990
Joe Rogan, Michael
Shermer and a few others.

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:27.240
This conversation is part of
the artificial intelligence

00:00:27.240 --> 00:00:30.270
podcast at MIT and Beyond.

00:00:30.270 --> 00:00:33.750
If you enjoy it, subscribe
on YouTube, iTunes,

00:00:33.750 --> 00:00:37.120
or simply connect with me
on Twitter @lexfridman,

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:39.420
spelled F-R-I-D.

00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:43.463
And now, here's my conversation
with Eric Weinstein.

00:00:44.610 --> 00:00:46.360
- Are you nervous about this?

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:47.260
- Scared shitless.

00:00:47.260 --> 00:00:48.470
- Okay, (speaking foreign language).

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:53.550
- You mention Kung Fu Panda as
one of your favorite movies.

00:00:54.610 --> 00:00:58.040
It has the usual profound
master student dynamic going on,

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:02.240
so who has been a teacher
that significantly influenced

00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:04.930
the direction of your
thinking and life's work?

00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:08.700
So, if you're the Kung Fu
Panda, who was your Shifu?

00:01:08.700 --> 00:01:09.533
- Oh, well that's interesting,

00:01:09.533 --> 00:01:12.160
because I didn't see Shifu
as being the teacher.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:13.830
- Who was the teacher?

00:01:13.830 --> 00:01:16.070
- Oogway, Master Oogway, the turtle.

00:01:16.070 --> 00:01:18.170
- Oh, the turtle, right.

00:01:18.170 --> 00:01:20.840
- They only meet twice in the entire film

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:24.003
and the first conversation
sort of doesn't count.

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:28.410
So, they magic of the
film, in fact, it's point

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:34.110
is that the teaching that
really matters is transferred

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:40.090
during a single conversation
and it's very brief.

00:01:40.090 --> 00:01:42.700
And so, who played that role in my life?

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:47.700
I would say either my
grandfather, Harry Rubin

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:54.053
and his wife Sophie Rubin,
my grandmother or Tom Lehrer.

00:01:55.040 --> 00:01:56.283
- Tom Lehrer?
- Yeah.

00:01:57.330 --> 00:01:58.163
- In which way?

00:01:58.163 --> 00:02:01.430
- If you give a child Tom Lehrer records,

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:04.250
what you do is you destroy their ability

00:02:04.250 --> 00:02:07.253
to be taken over by later malware,

00:02:08.090 --> 00:02:13.090
and it's so irreverent, so
witty, so clever, so obscene,

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:16.780
that it destroys the ability

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:19.360
to lead a normal life for many people.

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:24.360
So if I meet somebody who's
usually really shifted

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:27.160
from any kind of neuro
typical presentation,

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:30.710
I'll often ask them,
are you a Tom Lehrer fan

00:02:30.710 --> 00:02:34.160
and the odds that they will
respond are quite high.

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:37.590
- Now Tom Lehrer is Poisoning
Pigeons in the Park,

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:39.210
Tom Lehrer?
- That's very interesting.

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:41.440
There are a small number
of Tom Lehrer songs

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:43.840
that broke into the general population.

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:45.260
Poisoning Pigeons in the Park,

00:02:45.260 --> 00:02:47.683
the Element Song and
perhaps the Vatican Rag.

00:02:49.090 --> 00:02:51.500
So, when you meet somebody
who knows those songs,

00:02:51.500 --> 00:02:52.610
but doesn't know--

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:54.680
- Oh, you're judging me
right now, aren't you?

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:56.060
- Harshly.
- Okay.

00:02:56.060 --> 00:02:57.470
- No, but you're Russian, so.
- Yes.

00:02:57.470 --> 00:03:00.330
- Undoubtedly you know
Nikolai Ivanovich Lobachevsky.

00:03:00.330 --> 00:03:01.960
That song.
- Yes, yeah, yup.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:03.840
- So that was a song about plagiarism

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:05.560
that was in fact plagiarized,

00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:07.860
which most people don't
know, from Danny Kaye.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:10.680
Where Danny Kaye did a song called

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:13.000
Stanislavsky of the musky arts.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.300
And, so Tom Lehrer did this brilliant job

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:19.970
of plagiarizing a song and
making it about plagiarism,

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:22.540
and then making it about
this mathematician,

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:24.830
who worked in Non-Euclidean geometry.

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:27.570
That was like giving heroin to a child.

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:30.770
It was extremely addictive and eventually

00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:33.570
led me to a lot of different places.

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:36.570
One of which may have
been PhD in mathematics.

00:03:36.570 --> 00:03:39.610
- And he was also at least
a lecturer in mathematics,

00:03:39.610 --> 00:03:41.720
I believe at Harvard, something like that?

00:03:41.720 --> 00:03:44.750
- Yeah, I just had
dinner with him, in fact.

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:48.480
When my son turned 13, we didn't tell him,

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:52.770
but his Bar mitzvah present was dinner

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:54.370
with his hero, Tom Lehrer,

00:03:54.370 --> 00:03:58.810
and Tom Lehrer was 88
years old, sharp as a tack,

00:03:58.810 --> 00:04:03.350
irreverent and funny as
hell and just, you know,

00:04:03.350 --> 00:04:04.610
there are very few people in this world

00:04:04.610 --> 00:04:06.700
that you have to meet
while they're still here

00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:09.290
and that was definitely
one for our family.

00:04:09.290 --> 00:04:14.290
- So that wit is a
reflection of intelligence

00:04:14.690 --> 00:04:15.800
in some kind of deep way.

00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:17.770
Like where that would be a good test

00:04:17.770 --> 00:04:20.230
of intelligence whether
you're a Tom Lehrer fan.

00:04:20.230 --> 00:04:22.760
So, what do you think that is about wit?

00:04:22.760 --> 00:04:26.220
About that kind of humor,

00:04:26.220 --> 00:04:29.120
ability to see the absurdity in existence?

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:31.640
Do you think that's connected
to intelligence or are we just

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:34.720
two Jews on a mic that
appreciate that kind of humor.

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:36.690
- No, I think that it's absolutely

00:04:36.690 --> 00:04:37.970
connected to intelligence.

00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:41.890
You can see it, there's a
place where Tom Lehrer decides

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:45.840
that he's going to lampoon
Gilbert of Gilbert and Sullivan

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:47.870
and he's going to out
due Gilbert with clever,

00:04:47.870 --> 00:04:49.940
meaningless wordplay and he has,

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:53.030
I forget the, well let's see.

00:04:53.030 --> 00:04:55.980
He's doing Clementine as if
Gilbert and Sullivan wrote it

00:04:55.980 --> 00:04:57.410
and he says that I missed her,

00:04:57.410 --> 00:04:58.720
depressed her young sister named Esther.

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:00.160
This mister to pester she'd tried.

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:01.700
A pestering sister's a festering blister

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:03.510
you're best to resist her, say I!

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:05.040
The sister persisted, the mister resisted,

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:06.253
I kissed her, all loyalty slipped.

00:05:06.253 --> 00:05:08.440
When she said I could have
her her sister's cadaver

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:10.600
must surely have turned in its crypt.

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:11.870
That's so dense.

00:05:11.870 --> 00:05:13.810
It's so insane.
- Yeah.

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:17.530
- That that's clearly intelligence because

00:05:17.530 --> 00:05:19.540
it's hard to construct
something like that.

00:05:19.540 --> 00:05:24.540
If I look at my favorite
Tom Lehrer lyric, you know,

00:05:25.070 --> 00:05:26.930
there's a perfectly absurd one which is,

00:05:26.930 --> 00:05:28.820
once all the German's
were warlike and mean,

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:30.240
but that couldn't happen again.

00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:32.040
We taught them a lesson in 1918

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:34.150
and they've hardly bothered us since then.

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:35.440
- Right.
- That is a different

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:36.870
kind of intelligence.

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:39.810
You know, you're taking
something that is so horrific

00:05:39.810 --> 00:05:43.210
and you're sort of making
it palatable and funny,

00:05:43.210 --> 00:05:48.120
and demonstrating also just your humanity.

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:51.850
I mean, I think the thing that
came through as Tom Lehrer

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:55.240
wrote all of these
terrible, horrible lines,

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:58.060
was just what a sensitive
and beautiful soul he was,

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:01.883
who was channeling pain through
humor and through grace.

00:06:02.860 --> 00:06:04.960
- I've seen throughout
Europe, throughout Russia,

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:06.200
the same kind of humor emerged

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:09.240
from the generation of World War II.

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:12.240
It seemed like that humor
is required to somehow deal

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:16.010
with the pain and the suffering
of that that war created.

00:06:16.010 --> 00:06:17.940
- Well, you do need the environment

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:19.750
to create the broad Slavic soul.

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:24.530
I don't think that many
Americans really appreciate

00:06:25.900 --> 00:06:30.900
Russian humor, how you had
to joke during the time

00:06:31.310 --> 00:06:33.870
of let's say, Article 58 under Stalin.

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:35.660
You had to be very, very careful.

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:38.540
You know, the concept of a
Russian satirical magazine,

00:06:38.540 --> 00:06:41.410
like Krokodil, doesn't make sense.

00:06:41.410 --> 00:06:45.770
So you have this cross
cultural problem that there

00:06:45.770 --> 00:06:49.140
are certain areas of human
experience that it would

00:06:49.140 --> 00:06:53.470
be better to know nothing
about and quite unfortunately,

00:06:53.470 --> 00:06:55.670
eastern Europe knows a
great deal about them,

00:06:55.670 --> 00:07:00.033
which makes the songs of
Vladimir Voevodsky so potent.

00:07:01.606 --> 00:07:04.290
You know, the prose of
Pushkin, whatever it is.

00:07:04.290 --> 00:07:08.100
You have to appreciate the
depth of the Eastern European

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:11.740
experience and I would think
that perhaps Americans knew

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:15.590
something like this around
the time of the Civil War

00:07:15.590 --> 00:07:19.700
or maybe under slavery and Jim Crow

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:24.700
or even the harsh tyranny of the coal

00:07:24.810 --> 00:07:28.293
and steel employers during the labor wars.

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:33.040
But in general I would say,
it's hard for us to understand

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:36.080
and imagine the collective culture,

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:38.470
unless we have the system
of selective pressures,

00:07:38.470 --> 00:07:41.563
that for example, Russians
were subjected to.

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:46.750
- Yeah, so if there's one good
thing that comes outta war,

00:07:46.750 --> 00:07:51.750
it's literature, art and humor and music.

00:07:51.750 --> 00:07:54.380
- Oh, I don't think so. I
think almost everything is good

00:07:54.380 --> 00:07:57.040
about war except for
death and destruction.

00:07:57.040 --> 00:07:57.873
- Right.

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:02.690
Without the death it would
bring the romance of it,

00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:03.523
the whole thing is nice but--

00:08:03.523 --> 00:08:05.057
- Well, this is why we're
always caught up in war.

00:08:05.057 --> 00:08:08.350
We have this very ambiguous
relationship to it,

00:08:08.350 --> 00:08:12.800
is that it makes life real
and pressing and meaningful,

00:08:12.800 --> 00:08:15.870
and at an unacceptable price

00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:17.780
and the price has never been higher.

00:08:17.780 --> 00:08:22.253
- So to jump into AI a little bit,

00:08:24.750 --> 00:08:27.860
in one of the conversations
you had or one of the videos,

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:30.980
you described that one of the
things AI systems can't do

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:33.930
and biological systems
can is self replicate

00:08:33.930 --> 00:08:34.960
in the physical world.

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:35.960
- [Eric] Oh, no, no.

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:39.040
- In the physical world.

00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:40.410
- Well, yes.

00:08:40.410 --> 00:08:43.029
The physical robots can't self replicate,

00:08:43.029 --> 00:08:46.900
but there's a very tricky point,

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:49.570
which is that the only
thing that we've been able

00:08:49.570 --> 00:08:53.720
to create that's really
complex that has an analog

00:08:53.720 --> 00:08:57.340
of our reproductive system is software.

00:08:57.340 --> 00:09:01.880
- But, nevertheless,
software replicates itself,

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:04.090
if we're speaking strictly
for the replication

00:09:04.090 --> 00:09:06.110
is this kinda digital space.

00:09:06.110 --> 00:09:08.690
So let me, just to begin,
let me ask a question.

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:12.410
Do you see a protective barrier or a gap

00:09:12.410 --> 00:09:15.260
between the physical world
and the digital world?

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:16.440
- Let's not call it digital.

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:19.753
Let's call it the logical world
versus the physical world.

00:09:20.820 --> 00:09:21.840
- Why logical?

00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:24.170
- Well, because even though we had,

00:09:24.170 --> 00:09:26.423
let's say Einstein's brain preserved,

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:29.850
it was meaningless to
us as a physical object

00:09:29.850 --> 00:09:32.150
because we couldn't do anything with

00:09:32.150 --> 00:09:35.580
what was stored in it at a logical level.

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:38.450
And so, the idea that something
may be stored logically

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:43.450
and that it may be stored
physically, are not necessarily,

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:45.740
we don't always benefit from synonymizing.

00:09:45.740 --> 00:09:48.150
I'm not suggesting that
there isn't a material basis

00:09:48.150 --> 00:09:52.320
to the logical world,
but that it does warrant

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:54.080
identification with a separate layer that

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:59.080
need not invoke logic
gates and zeros and ones.

00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:01.420
- And, so connecting those two worlds,

00:10:01.420 --> 00:10:03.770
the logical world and the
physical world or maybe

00:10:03.770 --> 00:10:08.650
just connecting to the logical
world inside our brain,

00:10:08.650 --> 00:10:12.650
Einstein's brain, you mention
the idea of outtelligence.

00:10:14.330 --> 00:10:15.500
- [Eric] Artificial outtelligence.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:18.690
- Artificial outtelligence.
- Yes, this is the only essay

00:10:18.690 --> 00:10:21.800
that John Brockman every
invited me to write

00:10:21.800 --> 00:10:24.045
that he refused to publish in Edge.

00:10:24.045 --> 00:10:25.560
(Lex chuckling)

00:10:25.560 --> 00:10:26.790
- Why?

00:10:26.790 --> 00:10:30.440
- Well, maybe it wasn't well
written, but I don't know.

00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:32.500
- The idea is quite compelling.

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:37.230
It's quite unique and new, at
least from my stance point.

00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:38.310
Maybe you can explain it?

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:39.520
- Sure.

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:42.620
What I was thinking about is
why it is that we're waiting

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:47.300
to be terrified by artificial
general intelligence.

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:52.300
When in fact, artificial
life is terrifying

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:54.530
in and of itself and it's already here.

00:10:54.530 --> 00:10:57.820
So, in order to have a system
of selective pressures,

00:10:57.820 --> 00:11:00.210
you need three distinct elements.

00:11:00.210 --> 00:11:04.350
You need variation within a population,

00:11:04.350 --> 00:11:07.473
you need heritability, and
you need differential success.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:12.000
So, what's really unique
and I've made this point,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
I think elsewhere, about software,

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:17.970
is that if you think about what humans

00:11:17.970 --> 00:11:19.320
know how to build that's impressive.

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:21.960
So, I always take a car
and I say does it have

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:25.520
an analog of each of the
physiological systems?

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:27.880
Does it have a skeletal
structure, that's its frame.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:30.160
Does it have a neurological structure,

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:31.590
it has an onboard computer.

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:33.773
It has a digestive system.

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:38.420
The one thing it doesn't have
is a reproductive system.

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:42.950
But if you can call spawn on a process,

00:11:42.950 --> 00:11:45.250
effectively you do have
a reproductive system.

00:11:46.290 --> 00:11:49.720
And that means that you
can create something

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:53.380
with variation, heritability
and differential success.

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:55.780
Now, the next step in
the chain of thinking

00:11:55.780 --> 00:12:00.780
was where do we see inanimate
non intelligent life

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:04.373
outwitting intelligent life?

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:09.150
And I have two favorite
systems and I try to stay

00:12:09.150 --> 00:12:11.370
on them so that we don't get distracted.

00:12:11.370 --> 00:12:16.370
One of which is the Ophrys
orchid sub species or sub clave,

00:12:17.020 --> 00:12:17.853
I don't what to call it.

00:12:17.853 --> 00:12:20.290
- Is that a type of flower?
- Yeah, it's a type of flower

00:12:20.290 --> 00:12:23.480
that mimics the female
of a pollinator species

00:12:23.480 --> 00:12:27.580
in order to dupe the males
into engaging in what

00:12:27.580 --> 00:12:30.610
is called pseudocopulation,
with the fake female,

00:12:30.610 --> 00:12:33.730
which is usually represented
by the lowest pedal,

00:12:33.730 --> 00:12:36.450
and there's also a pheromone
component to fool the males

00:12:36.450 --> 00:12:37.990
into thinking they have
a mating opportunity.

00:12:37.990 --> 00:12:41.090
But the flower doesn't have
to give up energy in the form

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:44.093
of nectar as a lure, because
it's tricking the males.

00:12:45.300 --> 00:12:50.300
The other system is a
particular species of muscle,

00:12:50.600 --> 00:12:55.600
lampsilis in the clear streams
of Missouri and it fools bass

00:12:56.980 --> 00:13:01.900
into biting a fleshy lip that
contain its young and when

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:06.070
the bass see this fleshy
lip, which looks exactly like

00:13:06.070 --> 00:13:08.880
a species of fish that
the bass like to eat,

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:13.410
the young explode and clamp
onto the gills and parasitize

00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:16.620
the bass and also use
the bass to redistribute

00:13:16.620 --> 00:13:18.343
them as they eventually release.

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:24.450
Both of these systems, you
have a highly intelligent dupe,

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:29.143
being fooled by a lower life form.

00:13:30.330 --> 00:13:34.530
And what is sculpting
these convincing lures?

00:13:34.530 --> 00:13:37.160
It's the intelligence of previously

00:13:37.160 --> 00:13:41.470
duped targets for these strategies.

00:13:41.470 --> 00:13:44.803
So when the target is smart
enough to avoid the strategy,

